event: Youth Mental Health First Aid Training
description: This Children's Research Triangle (CRT) training is appropriate for teachers, parents, caregivers, mentors and any other adults in both a professional and paraprofessional capacity who are interested in learning how to identify, understand, and respond to signs of mental illness and substance use disorders. event: It Takes a Village: Comprehensive and Holistic Violence Prevention Panel Discussion
description:
Violence prevention is an ongoing topic of discussion in Chicago, but has received increased attention during the change of administration and as summer approaches. Although there are debates about the best method, research and experience suggests that effective violence prevention and recovery must take a comprehensive, multi-faceted approach. 

Join us for a discussion about the importance of holistic programming, examples of organizations/agencies that employ this approach, and the role each of us play in curbing the city's violence.

event: Strides for Peace: A Race Against Gun Violence

It is designed to strengthen awareness for programs building relationships with and supporting Chicagoans who have been affected by gun violence. The event features an 8K, 5K, 2-mile walk, and a Tots-for-Peace. It also includes entertainment from the Chicago Symphony Orchestra; beer and other refreshments; an opportunity to learn about various violence prevention programs; and the chance to spend a summer night outdoors. Visit here for information or to join the Catholic Charities/VPI racing team.

It also will feature a panel discussion with Communities Partnering 4 Peace, a unique collaboration of nine outreach organizations who have joined together to positively affect nine Chicago communities most affected by gun violence. State of Illinois Lieutenant Governor, The Honorable Julianna Stratton, will offer closing remarks on the administration's vision for its Justice, Equity and Opportunity Initiative. The event is free and open to the public. Lunch will be served and books will be available for purchase. RSVP by April 12.

La Unión Latina de Chicago es una organización de jornaleros y trabajadoras del hogar, basado en Albany Park y con programación en el noroeste y suroeste de Chicago. La Unión Latina ha abierto la inscripción para su próxima capacitación en salud y seguridad en construcción OSHA 10 en español. Se realizará la clase del 19 al 20 de mayo. Esta capacitación gratuita de dos días está diseñada para jornaleros, trabajadores informales en la industria de la construcción. Para registrarse, llame al 773-588-2641 y deje un mensaje para Armando.
Latino Union of Chicago is a membership-based organization of day laborers and household workers based in Albany Park that offers programming on Chicago's Northwest and Southwest Sides. Latino Union has opened registration for its next Spanish-language OSHA 10 construction health and safety training, which will be held May 19-20. This free two-day training is designed for day laborers, informal workers in the construction industry. To register, call 773-588-2641 and leave a message for Armando.

CDPH is hosting a free half-and-half buprenorphine waiver training for prescribers. This training allows any MD, DO, NP, or PA to complete 4 hours of training online and 4 hours of training in person. Physicians can then apply for the DATA waiver to prescribe buprenorphine. NPs and PAs then complete 16 more hours of training, which is also online and free.

event: The Time is Now - Sistas Uplifting Sistas on Health Equity, PrEP and Dismantling Racism
description:
Commemorating National Women & Girls HIV/AIDS Awareness Day 
The one-day conference will focus on identifying the combined impact of racism, trauma, and inequalities on the health outcomes of women and girls. Taking into consideration these factors, conference participants will gather information, tools, support, and affirmation to both confront systemic barriers and to consider solutions and strategies to improve HIV programming specifically for women and girls, inclusive of transgender persons.
This event is FREE! RSVP by March 12

event: Public Hearing on CDBG, HOME, ESG, and HOPWA Federal Funding to Chicago
description:
The public is invited to attend to provide comments on the 2017
Draft Comprehensive Annual Performance and Evaluation Report
(CAPER) and input on funding priorities for the 2019 Action Plan.
The CAPER and Action Plan cover the following U.S. Department
of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) Entitlement Programs:
Community Development Block Grants (CDBG)
HOME Investment Partnerships Grant (HOME)
Emergency Solutions Grant (ESG)
Housing Opportunities for Persons with AIDS (HOPWA)
The 2017 Draft CAPER is available for review at
www.cityofchicago.org/grants. Written comments will be
accepted through March 21, 2018.
Written comments on funding priorities for the 2019 Annual
Action Plan will be accepted through April 11, 2018.
